{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639003"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:03:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:03:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17757"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17757"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.76,0.02,0,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75970"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10471"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17757"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61471"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"646"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9924"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24441"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24444"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75970"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient has a left-sided tension pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the expected chest X-ray findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right lung collapse with mediastinal shift to the right","Left lung collapse with mediastinal shift to the right","Right lung collapse with mediastinal shift to the left","Bilateral lung collapse with no mediastinal shift","Left lung collapse with mediastinal shift to the left"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA tension pneumothorax occurs when air enters the pleural space and cannot escape, leading to increased intrathoracic pressure. This pressure causes the affected lung to collapse and pushes the mediastinum towards the opposite side. Here is a  example (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft lung collapse with mediastinal shift to the right\u003C/strong\u003E is the expected finding on a chest X-ray for a left-sided tension pneumothorax. The mediastinal structures, including the trachea, are pushed away from the affected side due to the pressure difference.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft lung collapse with mediastinal shift to the left\u003C/strong\u003E would not occur in a tension pneumothorax, as the mediastinum shifts away from the affected side, not towards it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight lung collapse with mediastinal shift to the left\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest a right-sided tension pneumothorax, which is not consistent with the clinical presentation of left-sided symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight lung collapse with mediastinal shift to the right\u003C/strong\u003E would also indicate a right-sided tension pneumothorax, which does not match the left-sided findings in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral lung collapse with no mediastinal shift\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical presentation of a tension pneumothorax, as this condition usually affects one side and causes a shift of the mediastinum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A tension pneumothorax is characterised by the accumulation of air in the pleural space, leading to ipsilateral lung collapse and contralateral mediastinal shift.","On a chest X-ray, a tension pneumothorax will show a visible pleural line with no vascular markings beyond it, indicating the presence of air in the pleural space.","Mediastinal shift away from the affected side is a key radiographic feature of a tension pneumothorax."],"references":["Leigh-Smith S, Harris T. Tension pneumothorax--time for a re-think? Emerg Med J. 2005 Jan;22(1):8-16. doi: 10.1136/emj.2003.010421. PMID: 15611534; PMCID: PMC1726546.","Zarogoulidis P, Kioumis I, Pitsiou G, Porpodis K, Lampaki S, Papaiwannou A, Katsikogiannis N, Zaric B, Branislav P, Secen N, Dryllis G, Machairiotis N, Rapti A, Zarogoulidis K. Pneumothorax: from definition to diagnosis and treatment. J Thorac Dis. 2014 Oct;6(Suppl 4):S372-6. doi: 10.3978/j.issn.2072-1439.2014.09.24. PMID: 25337391; PMCID: PMC4203989.","Jalota Sahota R, Sayad E. Tension Pneumothorax. 2024 Jan 30. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32644516.","McRoberts R, McKechnie M, Leigh-Smith S. Tension pneumothorax and the \u0022forbidden CXR\u0022. Emerg Med J. 2005 Aug;22(8):597-8. doi: 10.1136/emj.2004.018598. PMID: 16046774; PMCID: PMC1726896."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61471"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17757"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21391"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21391"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/keg2o1O86a9RB2mYeXzrRq8ZevAhLY.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/keg2o1O86a9RB2mYeXzrRq8ZevAhLY.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":416,"height":467}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61471"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T19:09:29+10:30","upda